Fiat, Generali, Intesa, Monte Paschi,Parmalat: Equity Preview for Italy

-- B y   M a r c o   B e r t a c c h e
-- 
2011-04-11T04:00:00Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-04-10/fiat-generali-intesa-parmalat-italian-equity-preview.html
The following companies may be
active in Italian trading. Stock symbols are in parentheses and
share prices are from the previous close.  Italy’s benchmark  FTSE MIB Index (FTSEMIB)  rose 145.16, or 0.7
percent, to 22,389.15 in Milan.  Assicurazioni Generali SpA (G)  : Italy’s biggest insurer
named Gabriele Galateri chairman after Cesare Geronzi quit. The
shares increased 1.3 percent to 16.26 euros  Banca Monte dei Paschi di Siena SpA (BMPS)  : Italy’s
third-biggest bank may call a board meeting this week to approve
a 2 billion-euro ($2.9 billion) rights offering, two people
familiar with the situation said April 5. The stock climbed 1.5
percent to 93.1 cents.  Eni SpA (ENI)  : Libyan unrest may cut Eni’s full-year
2011 production by 156,000 barrels a day, Il Sole 24 Ore
reported, without saying where it got the information.  The production cut likely won’t impact full-year results
and dividends, given higher  oil prices , the newspaper said. Eni
has a 2011 production target of 1.8 million barrels a day. The
stock rose 1.1 percent to 17.72 euros.  Fiat SpA (F)  : The Italian automaker that controls
Chrysler Group LLC is preparing to increase its stake in the
U.S. company to 30 percent from 25 percent as soon as this week,
two people familiar with the matter said April 8.  Separately, Automotive News Europe reported on its website
that Alfa Romeo’s return to the U.S. has been delayed by at
least six months to mid-2013, citing people with direct
knowledge of the matter. The stock fell 0.7 percent to 6.6
euros.  Intesa Sanpaolo SpA (ISP)  : Compagnia di San Paolo, the
biggest shareholder in Italy’s second-biggest bank, said it will
approve the bank’s proposal to sell new shares. The shares
dropped 1.1 percent to 2.26 euros.  Parmalat SpA (PLT)  : Parma’s court may have rejected
Groupe Lactalis’s appeal against a decision by the dairy maker
to move a shareholders meeting, Il Messaggero reported, without
saying where it got the information.  State lender Cassa Depositi e Prestiti is scheduled to hold
an extraordinary meeting to discuss a fund to invest in
“strategic” Italian companies, Finance Minister Giulio
Tremonti said April 9 at a briefing in Godollo, Hungary. He
declined to comment on the size of the fund. It will likely have
20 billion euros available, la Repubblica reported April 9.
Parmalat increased 0.9 percent to 2.298 euros.  To contact the reporter on this story:
